  "text": "A major advantage of the divide-and-conquer strategy (e.g. random forests) is its high efficiency in many timeconstraint vision tasks such as face detection and face alignment. Simple and ultrafast-to-compute features such as pixel difference, only extract sparse information (e.g. two pixels) from the image space. However, existing deep neural decision/regression forests [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] completely ignore the computational complexity of splitting nodes and in turn greatly limit their efficiency.",
